# Codex Workflow Rules

If this file is still located at `templates/AGENTS.md.template` inside the
workflow package, it is template source only and is not active rules for that
package. When installing the workflow package in a target repository, copy this
file to `AGENTS.md` and copy package source files from `agent/*.md` into target
repo `agent/*.md`. After installation as `AGENTS.md`, the rules below are
active for the target repository.

This installed file defines durable rules for Codex working in the target
repository. The main Codex session and every Codex subagent, worker, reviewer,
or verifier inherit these same rules, ticket scopes, approval boundaries, and
verification requirements. Keep it generic. Do not store one-off task history,
stale ticket details, machine-specific paths, private credentials, or
product-specific assumptions in this file.

## Target Repository Map

- `AGENTS.md` - durable Codex agent workflow rules.
- `steering/` - optional conditional guidance with YAML front matter that
  declares when specialized context should be loaded.
- `agent/` - repo-local state, decisions, known issues, and handoff notes.
- `tickets/` - scoped workflow records for non-trivial work.
- `specs/current/` - durable current specs for implemented behavior, contracts,
  workflows, and important constraints.
- `specs/changes/<change-id>/` - proposed change specs, typically
  `proposal.md`, `delta-spec.md`, `design.md`, and `tasks.md`.
- `specs/archive/` - accepted or closed change specs kept for history.
- `docs/` - reusable implementation paths, architecture notes, and proof
  records.
- `src/`, `app/`, `pages/`, `components/`, `lib/`, `server/`, `tests/`, and
  similar directories - product code, depending on the project.

## Required Read Order

Before planning or implementation work, read:

1. `AGENTS.md`
2. `steering/*.md` files whose front matter uses `inclusion.mode: always`
3. the newest relevant ticket in `tickets/`
4. steering files listed by
   `context_pack.required_steering_files`
5. steering files whose `inclusion.mode: fileMatch` patterns match the
   ticket's `allowed_files`
6. steering files whose `inclusion.mode: manual` files are explicitly named by
   the user, ticket, specs, or manager prompt
7. steering files whose `inclusion.mode: auto` description clearly matches the
   requested task, changed-file domain, or proof risk
8. `agent/STATE.md`
9. `agent/DECISIONS.md`
10. `agent/KNOWN_ISSUES.md`
11. `agent/TODO.md`
12. `agent/PATHS.md`
13. `agent/SERVICES.md`
14. `agent/CHANGELOG.md`
15. specs named by the ticket
16. docs named by the ticket
17. files in the ticket's allowed scope

Build a bounded context pack before implementation. Include only the steering
files selected by the rules above, and record intentionally excluded noisy or
irrelevant context in `context_pack.excluded_context` when the ticket needs that
decision preserved. Do not load private/global machine paths, secrets, or
product-specific assumptions into steering files.

If a referenced file is missing, stale, or conflicts with the current user
instruction, report that fact instead of silently filling the gap.

On the first read in a fresh project or after adding `agent/` templates, inspect
the repository stack before implementation starts and propose initial `agent`
entries. Use repo evidence such as package manifests, lockfiles, framework
config, test config, build config, CI files, Docker/compose files, environment
examples, scripts, and existing docs. Suggest updates for `agent/STATE.md`,
`agent/PATHS.md`, `agent/SERVICES.md`, `agent/KNOWN_ISSUES.md`, and
`agent/TODO.md`. Do not invent unknown values; mark them as unknown and write
updates only when they are inside the active ticket scope or the user approves
the bootstrap update.

When inspecting environment examples, use filenames and variable names only.
Do not read, print, copy, create, or modify secret values or private environment
files.

## Ticketed Workflow

- Non-trivial planning and implementation work must be ticketed.
- Planning work must create or update a scoped ticket before implementation
  starts.
- Non-trivial implementation work must link requirements, design, and tasks
  specs, or record a justified quick-flow exemption in the ticket before
  product-code work starts.
- Significant behavior, API, data, workflow, or durable documentation changes
  must link a delta spec under `specs/changes/<change-id>/delta-spec.md` or
  record why the delta-spec lifecycle does not apply.
- Codex implementation workers must work from the active ticket scope and keep changes
  inside the ticket's declared files unless the user widens scope.
- After each meaningful step, record the result as a ticket comment or result
  note. Include proof, changed files, blockers, and next action.
- A ticket may be marked `done` only after required proof has been collected and
  recorded.
- If proof is missing, leave the ticket non-done and report the missing proof.
- Completed tickets must include a human-readable `execution_result` block.
- Before closing any ticket, explicitly check whether `agent/STATE.md`,
  `agent/DECISIONS.md`, `agent/KNOWN_ISSUES.md`, `agent/TODO.md`,
  `agent/PATHS.md`, `agent/SERVICES.md`, or `agent/CHANGELOG.md` need an
  update. If they do, update them inside the ticket scope or record why the
  update is deferred. If they do not, record `agent memory checked: no update
  needed` in the ticket result.
- Before closing significant changes, merge accepted `ADDED`, `MODIFIED`, and
  `REMOVED` delta-spec items into `specs/current/**` and archive the change
  package under `specs/archive/<date>-<change-id>/`, or record a deferred spec
  update blocker in the ticket result.
- If parallel tickets touch the same `specs/current/**` file or requirement ID,
  stop and reconcile the conflict before implementation continues or either
  ticket archives its delta.
- Stage only files in the ticket scope plus the ticket record. Do not use bulk
  staging such as `git add -A`.
- Do not revert changes you did not make unless explicitly requested.

## Safety And Approval Boundaries

Forbidden unless the user explicitly requests or approves the exact action:

- installing, upgrading, or removing dependencies
- running destructive commands that delete, overwrite, reset, or discard work
- running schema, data, or storage migrations with side effects
- editing secrets, credentials, tokens, `.env`, or private local configuration
- running network-dependent setup or external-service commands not already
  approved by the ticket
- pushing, force-pushing, releasing, deploying, publishing, or modifying remotes
- committing or checkpointing when the ticket does not assign that action
- widening ticket scope beyond `allowed_files`
- changing application behavior outside the active ticket objective
- broad staging such as `git add -A`
- committing secrets, local private paths, generated caches, dependency folders,
  or build output
- writing run logs, review notes, transient conversation notes, or closeout
  reports outside the ticket/result locations defined by the workflow

Normally allowed inside the active scope:

- reading repository files and metadata
- editing files listed in `allowed_files`
- creating or updating tickets and `agent/*.md` entries required by the ticket
- running repo-local format, lint, typecheck, test, build, and proof commands
  that do not install dependencies or mutate external systems
- adding focused tests or docs required by the ticket

When a command may contact external services, mutate persistent state, or depend
on credentials, record the risk and ask before running it unless the active
ticket already grants that permission.

## Ticket Planning Contract

Every implementation ticket must include these fields before product-code work:

- `context_pack.required_steering_files`
- `context_pack.excluded_context`
- `spec_refs`, or a justified `spec_contract.quick_flow_exemption`
- `spec_contract`
- `execution_intensity`
- `manager_role`
- `worker_sequence`
- `expert_plan`
- `debug_logging_plan`
- `test_plan`
- `proof_gates`
- `regression_gates`
- `visual_gate`
- `checkpoint_policy`
- `rollback_or_accept_policy`
- `stop_conditions`
- `allowed_files`
- `forbidden_files`
- `handoff_requirements`
- `done_definition`

The `test_plan` or closeout proof must include an agent-memory update check for
`agent/` files whenever the ticket changes durable project state, decisions,
known issues, setup paths, service assumptions, or follow-up work.

For non-trivial work, the ticket's `spec_refs` point to the requirements,
design, and tasks artifacts that act as source of truth with `AGENTS.md` and
agent memory. The specs must keep acceptance criteria, design boundaries,
allowed-file tasks, proof, and requirement traceability aligned. Tiny quick-flow
changes may skip full specs only when the ticket records a concrete exemption
reason.

For significant changes, `spec_refs` should also include the delta spec. The
delta spec uses `ADDED`, `MODIFIED`, and `REMOVED` sections to describe how
`specs/current/**` must change. Final verification checks that implementation
matches the delta intent and that the current spec update was merged, archived,
or explicitly deferred with a blocker.

The `test_plan` must list concrete checks that decide whether the ticket may be
marked done. For web applications, use relevant repo-local checks such as:

- formatter checks
- lint checks
- type checks
- unit tests
- integration tests
- build checks
- database migration checks
- API contract checks
- accessibility checks
- Playwright or browser-based visual/flow checks

Complex, risky, visual, diagnostic, performance-sensitive, or reviewer-backed
tickets must include a read-only Codex planning or review subagent before
implementation. Diagnostic and performance tickets must name a debug/logging
owner.

## Execution Intensities

- `standard_worker`: one scoped Codex worker, direct proof, scoped checkpoint.
- `expert_supported`: one read-only Codex planning or review subagent, then one
  scoped Codex worker.
- `bounded_expert_rounds`: iterative blocker or complex-feature loop with a
  fixed iteration cap, default maximum five.
- `research_only`: read-only Codex reviewers analyze and recommend; product
  files do not change.

## Codex Subagent Rules

- Codex subagents follow this `AGENTS.md`, the active ticket, approval
  boundaries, forbidden actions, and verification requirements.
- The main Codex agent acts as manager/observer for complex tickets.
- The manager keeps global context, owns scope, chooses the next action, and
  reviews subagent output before continuing.
- Run exactly one implementation worker at a time unless the ticket explicitly
  declares disjoint write scopes.
- Independent read-only Codex reviewers may run in parallel only when the ticket
  allows it and their questions are distinct.
- Codex workers receive a narrow file scope and must not edit outside it.
- Codex workers must report changed files, commands run, proof, blockers, and
  risks to the manager.
- Codex subagents must not write logs, memory files, closeout reports, or review
  notes unless those files are inside the active ticket scope.
- A bounded expert round runs: gather proof, ask a read-only Codex reviewer,
  choose one bounded worker task, run one worker, run proof, then checkpoint or
  record blocker.
- Stop if an iteration is worse than the previous accepted state or if the
  iteration cap is reached.

## Verification

Verification is part of the task, not an optional epilogue.

Before marking a ticket done:

- run every command in `test_plan` that is available in the repo
- inspect relevant UI behavior when user-facing frontend changes were made
- capture screenshots or recordings when required by `visual_gate`
- record failed commands exactly enough for the next Codex session to reproduce
- record skipped checks with a concrete reason

## Completion Report

Every completed ticket must end with `execution_result` or a clearly named
completion block that states:

- what changed
- what intentionally did not change
- changed files
- commands run
- proof collected
- skipped proof and why
- blockers, if any
- risks, if any
- whether a human smoke test is useful
- exact next recommended step
- agent memory files updated or `agent memory checked: no update needed`

## Commit Policy

- Commit only after the ticket is done or after explicit user approval for a
  checkpoint.
- Use scoped staging with explicit paths.
- Commit message format:

```text
TKT-YYYY-MM-DD-short-name: concise result
```

- Do not include unrelated files in the commit.
